x4freetext: K.WISSHAK, Description of
detector.
3.7 MV Van de Graaff accelerator.
Flight path is 79 cm for capture and 260 cm for
total cross section measurements
Karlsruhe 4pi barium fluoride detector for
detection of capture gamma-rays. Detector consists
of 42 hexagonal and pentagonal crystals forming a
spherical shell of baf(2) with 10 cm inner radius
and 15 cm thickness. Resolution of energy is 7%
at 2.5 MeV, time resolution 500 picosec, peak effi-
ciency 90% at 1 MeV. The 1.8-MeV gamma-ray
threshold in sum energy used in the present
experiment corresponds to an efficiency for capture
events of more than 95%.
Li-6 glass detectors for neutron total cross-
section measurement
Metallic Li target.
.Proton beam energy adjusted so to be 30 and 100 KeV
above the Li-7(P,N)be-7 reaction threshold 1.881 MeV.
.Au-197 sample 10 mm diameter, 0.4  mm = 2.1621E-3
atoms/B thickness, 0.5554-gram weight, enclosing
in welded titanium can, lid and body deep-drawn from
0.25-mm thick foils- 0.4329g
.Empty welded titanium can, lid and body deep-drawn
from 0.25-mm thick foils- 0.4181g
.Corrections were made for multiple scattering,
for isotopic impurities, for neutron self-absorption,
for undetected events, for signal/background ratio -
all for different neutron energies-these corrections
are smaller than 2%.

.A 206.4 mg samples of samarium oxide Sm2-O3 with 90%
enrichment in Sm-151 were used. It was pressed into
a solid pellet 10 mm in diameter, which was enclosed
in a titanium can prepared from 0.25 mm thick foil
0.4340g weight. Thickness is 0.6 mm=0.8861E-3 at/B.
The can consisted of a deep-drawn body 15 mm in
diameter with a 3 mm deep depression for the sample.
The lid had a corresponding depression of 1 mm to
match the 2-mm thick sample. An identical sample was
prepared from natural samarium oxide to verify the
experimental procedures by checking whether the cross
section of natural samarium could be properly
reproduced.
*By authors*.For easier comparison of the individual
results the averaged total cross sections in the
neutron energy interval from 10 to 100-KeV are
indicated as well-17.2 barns.

x4freetext: Data for ASSUM1,

The neutron energy range from thermal to 700-KeV was
divided into three intervals-I(X). The dominant part
between 3 and 225-KeV (I2) is provided by the present
experiments. These data were obtained with sufficient
resolution in neutron energy to exclude systematic
uncertainties in the calculation of the maxwellian
average. Contributions for 0-3 =I(1) and 225-700 keV
= I(3) are taken from REL-REF being normalized to the
present data.
